habitat_description:
Found in desert and coastal streams to pine belt mountains usually in rapidly flowing water. Population occur disjointly in the mountains of south California including desert streams and oases in the desert slope of Peninsular Ranges, Forty-nine palms, Indian Cove; also occurs south into Baja California, south Catavina (Las Palmas). Other isolated populations are reported in Sierra de Juarez and San Pedro Martir (Stebbins 2003). In California, this species is found in the Coast Ranges from San Luis Obispo County, through the Transverse Ranges, Joshua Tree National Park, and south up to the Mexican border (Lannoo 2005). Current exact distribution is unknown due to difficulty locating the treefrogs in presumably suitable habitat (Lannoo 2005). Earlier studies by Greene and Luke 1996 reported an isolated population in the Granite Mountains, Granite Mountains Preserve in the Mojave Desert.

Adults and juveniles are primarily found in proximity to water (less than 150 ft) (Cunningham 1964) although have been reported to bask in direct sunlight (Lannoo 2005).
